[30;1m236 | [0m[35mACLs[0m
[30;1m237 | [0m[35m====[0m
[30;1m238 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m239 | [0m[35mAccess Control List (ACL) feature in Barbican provides user level access[0m
[30;1m240 | [0m[35mcontrol for secrets and containers. By default Barbican manages access to its[0m
[30;1m241 | [0m[35mresources (secrets, containers) on a per project level and authorization is[0m
[30;1m242 | [0m[35mgranted based on the roles a user has in that project.[0m
[30;1m243 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m236 | [0m[35mACLs[0m
[30;1m237 | [0m[35m====[0m
[30;1m238 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m239 | [0m[35mAccess Control List (ACL) feature in Barbican provides user level access[0m
[30;1m240 | [0m[35mcontrol for secrets and containers. By default Barbican manages access to its[0m
[30;1m241 | [0m[35mresources (secrets, containers) on a per project level and authorization is[0m
[30;1m242 | [0m[35mgranted based on the roles a user has in that project.[0m

[30;1m90 | [0m[35m   Previous versions of python-barbicanclient allowed the user to set the[0m
[30;1m91 | [0m[35m   `payload_content_type` and `payload_content_encoding` properties for any[0m
[30;1m92 | [0m[35m   secret.  This can lead to unexpected behavior such as changing a unicode[0m
[30;1m93 | [0m[35m   string back to a byte string in Python 2, and dropping the base64 encoding[0m
[30;1m94 | [0m[35m   of a binary secret as in Launchpad Bug #1419166.[0m
[30;1m95 | [0m[35m   Because of this, manually setting the `payload_content_type` and the[0m
[30;1m96 | [0m[35m   `payload_content_encoding` has been deprecated.[0m

[30;1m78 | [0m[35m`Secret.payload` property.  The following table summarizes the mapping of[0m
[30;1m79 | [0m[35mPython types to Barbican Secret Content Types:[0m

[30;1m155 | [0m[35mthe line of the API call you wish to test. For example, adding the breakpoint[0m

[30;1m157 | [0m[35mbreakpoint whenever the ``create`` function is called.[0m
